The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 Saturday, September 25, 2004 

 Flood shadow on vegetable bazaar

 OUR BUREAU

 Sept. 24: The spectre of a vegetable price hike looms over the state with hundreds of acres in at least five districts still under water. 

 Agriculture minister Kamal Guha, principal secretary of the department S. Barma, director of agriculture Dhabaleswar Konar and officials from Murshidabad, Nadia, North 24-Parganas, Birbhum and Burdwan met at Writers? Buildings today to take stock of the situation in the wake of the floods. 

 An estimated Rs 250 crore worth of crops has been destroyed. More than three-quarters of the crops damaged are vegetables. 

 A senior agriculture department official said: ?We are apprehending a rise in the price of vegetables, which might continue till the puja. The crops damaged were supposed to be stocked till that time.? He added that attempts were on to combat the scarcity. Seeds of various vegetables will be sent to the districts immediately. 

 Konar said: ?We are trying to make vegetables available in the market from various sources. Potatoes lying in the cold storage will come to good use now. We are also trying to encourage plantation of vegetables that grow fast like spinach and radish.?

 Finance minister Asim Dasgupta today visited parts of Nadia and North 24-Parganas affected by the flood. At least 17 out of 19 blocks in Nadia were affected and 11,000 houses destroyed.




